### Salary Takeaway

The salary analysis confirms a substantial **AI premium**. AI-related postings consistently show higher median salaries than non-AI postings across virtually every state. This aligns with national data: the BLS reported that the median annual wage for computer and IT occupations reached $105,990 in May 2024, well above the national median for all occupations. The ITIF estimated that AI-driven sectors saw 16.7% wage growth since fall 2022, compared to just 7.5% nationally. The state-by-state median salary chart reveals that this premium is not uniform — it tends to be largest in states with the highest AI intensity (CA, WA, MA, NY), where competition for AI talent drives wages upward. In Sun Belt states with lower AI intensity, the AI premium exists but is narrower, reflecting less specialized demand.

## 3.6 Top Skills: AI vs. Non-AI

::: {#cell-skills .cell execution_count=9}
``` {.python .cell-code code-summary="Most demanded skills in AI vs Non-AI postings"}
results = []
for cat in ['AI-Related', 'Non-AI']:
    subset = df[df['job_category'] == cat]
    total = len(subset)
    sk = subset['skills_name'].explode()
    sk = sk[sk != '']
    for skill, count in sk.value_counts().head(20).items():
        results.append({'Skill': skill, 'Category': cat, 'Pct': round(count/total*100, 1)})

skill_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
top_skills = set(skill_df[skill_df['Category']=='AI-Related'].nlargest(15,'Pct')['Skill']) | \
             set(skill_df[skill_df['Category']=='Non-AI'].nlargest(15,'Pct')['Skill'])

fig = px.bar(skill_df[skill_df['Skill'].isin(top_skills)],
    x='Pct', y='Skill', color='Category', barmode='group', orientation='h',
    title="Figure 9: Top Skills — AI vs. Non-AI (% of postings)",
    labels={'Pct':'% of Postings','Skill':''},
    color_discrete_map={'AI-Related':'#3498db','Non-AI':'#e74c3c'})
fig.update_layout(
    yaxis=dict(
        autorange="reversed",
        automargin=True,
        tickfont=dict(size=11)
    ),
    height=750,
    width=1000,
    margin=dict(l=250, r=80, t=80, b=60)
)
fig.show()
