### Skills Takeaway

The skills comparison reveals a clear divide between the two career tracks. AI postings are much more concentrated around technical skills such as Python, machine learning, SQL, cloud platforms, and deep learning frameworks like TensorFlow and PyTorch. Non-AI postings, by contrast, place more emphasis on communication, project management, Excel, finance, and other domain-specific skills.
This difference has important implications. Job seekers targeting AI roles face a more technical skill barrier than those pursuing non-AI roles, which helps explain why AI hiring is more geographically concentrated. These jobs depend on specialized talent pipelines that are often connected to research universities, technology firms, and established innovation ecosystems. This pattern is also consistent with LinkedIn’s 2025 Future of Work Report, which identifies machine learning and AI-related skills as among the fastest-growing skill categories globally.

