### Texas: The Bridge State

Texas is perhaps the most interesting case. It ranks **#2 in both AI volume** (UMD-LinkUp) **and broad talent attraction** (Lightcast Scorecard). BLS data confirms this: Texas added 284,200 jobs in 2024 — the most of any state — while also maintaining one of the largest absolute counts of AI postings. It is one of the few states that performs exceptionally on both dimensions, making it uniquely competitive for job seekers targeting either AI or non-AI paths. Austin and Dallas–Fort Worth function as "bridge metros" that combine rapid overall growth with a strong and rising AI ecosystem.

### Broader Context: AI Job Creation vs. Displacement

The broader national picture provides important context for these geographic patterns. According to the Information Technology and Innovation Foundation (ITIF), AI created approximately 119,900 direct jobs in the U.S. in 2024, including 8,900 roles specifically for developing and operating AI models and over 110,000 construction jobs tied to data center expansion. In contrast, an estimated 12,700 jobs were lost due to AI that same year — meaning AI created roughly **9 jobs for every 1 it displaced**. The Stanford AI Index further notes that the share of U.S. job postings requiring AI skills rose from 1.4% to 1.8% between 2023 and 2024, while generative AI job postings surged 323% year-over-year. These national trends are reflected in our geographic findings: the states leading AI job creation are the same states where these new roles and data center investments are concentrated.

